e pragmatist philosophy of the humanities defended by Pihlström takes a distinctively Kantian critical turn in emphasizing the need for transcendental argumentation in the philosophy of the humanities, insisting on the irreducibly ethical dimensions of humanistic scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aHumanitiesxPhilosophy. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aPragmatism. 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 4aHistory : History. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Spirituality. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Pragmatism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849107340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438491073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438491073/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles